      "uniqueness": "The important difference from Namecoin-family AuxPoW is format and parent scope. Hathor uses the ASCII `Hath` commitment marker, RFC 0006 defines no chain ID or strict chain-ID field, and the parent can be any SHA-256d chain.[^6] Bitcoin relevance is therefore a classification result, not something assumed from the Hathor block itself.",
      "capture": "The monitor reads Hathor through the public REST API because mainnet is permissioned for node operation. For each candidate block, it reconstructs the SHA-256d parent header from the split-header proof, verifies the reconstruction identity, checks Bitcoin proof of work, and filters non-Bitcoin SHA-256d parents through the `nBits` table. Bitcoin Core then places known parent hashes as canonical or stale; Core-absent Hathor parents are weak orphan evidence because the proof does not provide a trustworthy BIP34 Bitcoin coinbase height.",
      "bitcoin_relevance": "Hathor is useful after filtering, not because every Hathor parent is Bitcoin. Its short block interval creates many chances to observe a BTC parent, but the recovered stale signal mostly corroborates older merge-mined sources.",
